eligious conversion, often confirming religious belief, but also how women could advise others about their physical and spiritual health in manuscript and print. The anthology includes a thorough introduction to the period’s medical and religious beliefs, as well as an introduction to contemporary ideas about women’s physical and spiritual make up. Each of the ten extracts also has its own preface, highlighting relevant contexts and further reading, and is fully annotated.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aEnglish literaturexWomen authors. 0aEnglish literatureyEarly modern, 1500-1700. 0aEnglish literature. 0aWomenzGreat BritainvLiterary collections. 4amanchesterhive variable pricing textbooks. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aConversion.  aHealth.  aIllness.  aMedicine.  aPregnancy.  aReligion.  aSeventeenth-century women.  aSuicide.  aWomen's writing.1 aAdcock, Rachel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAdcock, Rachel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRead, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRead, Sara, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aZiomek, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZiomek, Anna, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2014 eBook-Packagez9783111283579oZDB-23-MUP40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526111012423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526111012/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-MUPb2014